Background

In class, we discussed two broad subfields of machine learning: supervised learning and unsupervised learning. In a typical supervised learning setup, we use a set of labeled input data points to try and learn a robust function that maps future inputs to labels. By contrast, in unsupervised learning, we do not have labels for our training data, and instead we seek to understand interesting things about the data such as the correlation structure between variables or whether high-dimensional data points can be projected into a lower-dimensional space without much loss of information. In this assignment, we will explore both approaches to machine learning using the same dataset.

Question 5

You suggest to your collaborator that you should divide the sample into a training and test dataset. Write a function called train_test_split that accepts hw2.data as an input and returns an R list object containing two tibbles: train and test in a 70:30 random split.

train_test_split <- function(hw2.data) {
  hw2.train <- hw2.data %>% sample_frac(0.7)
  hw2.test <- anti_join(hw2.data, hw2.train, by = NULL)
  train_test_split <- list()
  train_test_split[[1]] <- hw2.train
  train_test_split[[2]] <- hw2.test
  return(train_test_split)
}

Part 2: Unsupervised Learning

Now lets switch gears to unsupervised learning. First well simulate a dataset with known correlation structure and then well explore the same coronary artery disease dataset from Part 1 using techniques from unsupervised learning.

Question 11

Consider a toy dataset consisting of four variables, x1, x2, x3, and x4. Write an R function called simulate that simulates 10,000 observations of such a dataset with only two constraints: that the correlation = 0.8 between x1 and x2 and the correlation = 0.55 between x3 and x4 [Hint: use the mvrnorm function from the R package MASS already installed on the server].

# your code here
# Assume the mean of all variables = 0, variance of all variables = 1, write function
simulation <- function(n = 10000, seed=37){
  #setting the covariance matrix values. The "2,2" part defines the number of rows and columns
  sigma1 <- matrix(c(1, 0.8, 0.8, 1), 2,2)  # set the correlation of 0.8 for variable x1 and x1
  sigma2 <- matrix(c(1, 0.55, 0.55, 1), 2,2)  # set the correlation of 0.55 for variable x3 and x4
  #set the seed value
  set.seed(seed)
  #simulate the data, as specified above
  sim1 <- mvrnorm(n, mu = c(0,0), Sigma = sigma1)
  sim2 <- mvrnorm(n, mu = c(0,0), Sigma = sigma2)
  sim <- cbind(sim1, sim2)
  colnames(sim) <- c('x1','x2','x3','x4')
  return(data.frame(sim))
}

Question 16

Run PCA on all the blood labs in the full hw2.data dataset (make sure to select only variables that start with LBX). Make sure to center and scale PCA. Why is it important to center and scale? Plot the variance explained by principal component.

# your code here
# select only lab results
hw2.lab <- hw2.data %>% select(-cad, -age, -gender)
hw2.pca <- prcomp(hw2.lab, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
fviz_pca_biplot(hw2.pca, repel = TRUE, label = "none",
                col.var = "#E2485B",
                col.ind = "#3A5175"
                )

fviz_eig(hw2.pca, addlabels=TRUE, barfill = "#E2485B", linecolor = "#3A5175")+
labs(title = "Scree plot",
         x = "Dimentions", y = "Percentage of explained variances")

  • Centering can help to compare the variation of the data instead of the absolute value of the data. So when the PCs go through the origin point, it can span the direction of the most variations.
  • Scaling different variables so that they are equivalent and comparable to each other, otherwise will cause biases towards one of them.
